      "writtenOn": "2020-05-21T01:02:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "i like Vadim\u0027s approach I saw yesterday on validating token server requests:\n\nall validate*() funcs return plain error, which removes the need to copy-pasta \"codes.InvalidArgument\" everywhere. It also makes it easy to outsource sub-validate calls.\n\nFor example, when validating builderID{project, bucket, builder} is done in several places. This would be possible:\n\nvalidateBuilderID(proto) error {\n case proto.bucket \u003d\u003d \"\":\n   return errors.New(\"bucket is required\")\n}\n\nvalidateXYZ(proto) error {\n  if err :\u003d validateBuilderID(proto.some_field); err !\u003d nil {\n    return errors.Reason(\"some_filed: %s\",  err)\n  }\n}\n\n\nxyzHandler(){\n  if err:\u003d validateXYZ(); err !\u003d nil {\n    return appstatus.Errorf(codes.InvalidArgument, err.Error())\n  }\n}",
      "revId": "b2b44616566e14d35f595fea5cf4fb10dab9a883",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d58b57ba_f6cceff8",
        "filename": "buildbucket/appengine/rpc/get_build.go",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 45,
      "author": {
        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-21T18:01:01Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003eeasy to outsource sub-validate calls\nWhy is it difficult now? This function calls validateBuilderID just fine.\n\nI could imagine a case where validation itself fails and we want to return an internal error, so assuming validation returns something to which InvalidArgument must always be attached may not be correct.",
      "parentUuid": "4813106e_c393ce31",
